  "texts": [
    "These results validate that the z-σ threshold, combined with soft rejection, provides superior stability compared to τ I and effectively maintains greater robustness than MZ.",
    "ConclusionsWe propose Adaptive and Aggressive Rejection (AAR), a novel anomaly detection framework that dynamically evolves its rejection policy as the model learns.",
    "In the early phase, AAR applies a robust hard rejection -anchoring training on high-confidence normal samples via a modified z-score threshold -to stabilize optimization.",
    "As anomaly scoring matures, it transitions to aggressive rejection, deliberately setting a higher cutoff than the true contamination ratio to maximize robustness when the normal and abnormal score distributions overlap.",
    "At this stage, AAR fits a Gaussian Mixture Model to estimate the normal-anomaly boundary to down-weighting borderline samples instead of discarding them outright."
